For the NbTa binary solid solution, its σ y is 246 ± 14 MPa, comparable to that of pure Nb and Ta  [28, 29] , suggesting that mixing of Nb and Ta does not generate pronounced solution hardening, consistent with previous findings  [26, 30, 31] . The tensile strain to failure, ε f , is over 20%, showing the excellent ductility of this alloy.
Alloying the NbTa with Ti to form the TiNbTa MEA nearly doubles the σ y to 478 MPa, with only minor reduction of ε f .

For ternary HfNbTa, its σ y reaches as high as 847 MPa, a three-fold increase over the NbTa binary. Evidently, alloying with Hf has a much higher strengthening potency than Ti  [25] . The HfNbTa RMEA also shows a high σ uts of 889 MPa. However, the ε f is reduced to < 10%.
The TiHfNbTa quaternary produces an intermediate σ y of 663 MPa in between the TiNbTa and the HfNbTa, with an ε f similar to the latter.
The TiNbTa RMEA has a tensile ductility in excess of 20%, while its yield strength is < 500 MPa.
Moreover, HfNbTa has a combination of yield strength and tensile ductility comparable with its RHEA counterpart TiZrHfNbTa, the Senkov alloy.
